  "response_text": "Certainly! The classes P, NP, and NP-complete are fundamental concepts in computational complexity theory, which deals with the classification of computational problems based on their inherent difficulty.\n\n### 1. P (Polynomial Time)\n\n**Definition:** A problem is in the class P if it can be solved in polynomial time. This means that there exists an algorithm that can solve the problem in O(n^k) time, where n is the size of the input and k is some constant.\n\n**Example:**\n- **Sorting:** Algorithms like QuickSort or MergeSort can sort a list of n elements in O(n log n) time, which is polynomial.\n- **Shortest Path in a Graph:** Dijkstra's algorithm can find the shortest path from a source to all other vertices in a graph in O((V + E) log V), where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges. This is also polynomial.\n\n### 2. NP (Nondeterministic Polynomial Time",
